`ThrowingConstructorService` and how class initialization works during testing to avoid errors.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying instantiation behavior**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how `InstantiatableClass.newInstance` uses `Class.newInstance()`, which is deprecated in Java 9. It's interesting that `Class.newInstance` propagates any exceptions thrown by the constructor directly. According to the JDK documentation, exceptions from a nullary constructor are also propagated, so an `ArithmeticException` will come through too, which I think is fine to assert. As for `InvokableConstructor.newInstance`, it’s good to note that this library unwraps exceptions. That definitely clarifies things a bit!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented comprehensive Scala tests in:\n\n`tests/src/org.portable-scala/portable-scala-reflect_2.13/1.1.1/src/test/scala/org_portable_scala/portable_scala_reflect_2_13/Portable_scala_reflect_2_13Test.scala`\n\nCovered:\n- Annotated class lookup and instantiation\n- Public constructor discovery/invocation\n- Missing constructor behavior\n- Constructor exception unwrapping\n- Inherited annotations from traits/superclasses\n- Rejection of unsupported/unannotated/local/abstract/private-constructor classes\n- Annotated inner class instantiation with outer instance\n- Module lookup/loading\n- Module initialization timing\n- Inherited module annotations\n- Invalid module/class lookup cases\n- Module initialization exception unwrapping\n- Macro overloads using current classloader\n\nNo build files or metadata/config files were modified, and I did not compile or run tests.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_047871b232417e680169fb44d22c3c81a194e9819ea8bfd577\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 606, "output": 1185, "cacheRead": 38912, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 40703, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 